description: Provided varied, detailed, time-sensitive intelligence products to federal, state, and local law enforcement agencies as well as other first responders in the state of Colorado as well as other national Fusion Centers. Extensive knowledge of Law Enforcement databases, Department of Homeland Security databases, as well as CLEAR, LEO, TLOex, Accurent, CCIC, and various auto theft research programs and sites. Helped to provide Terrorism Liaison Officer (TLO) training to over 110 law enforcement and first responders. Developed and provided classified and unclassified Bi-Monthly intelligence briefings to partners from the FBI, DHS, NSA, the Director of Safety and Preparedness for the State of Colorado, Chief of the Colorado State Patrol as well as other local law enforcement and first responder leadership. Produced over 100 intensive, detailed reports including Threat Analysis, Threat review, Law Enforcement Intel Bulletins, federal and state terrorism and counter-terrorism reports and presentations.

description: Managed and directed all aspects of an employee-owned small business of over 60 employees, with 12 employees directly reportable to the President. Responsibilities of the President included: · Day-to-day oversight of program managers, project managers and overhead support personnel including contracts, finance, logistics and security personnel · Development, management, and execution of the TMA overhead plan and oversight and management of all overhead pools. · Retirement plan sponsor and oversight for the TMA 401(k)/Profit sharing plan and the TMA ESOP. · Registered Agent for TMA's Incentive Stock Option (ISO) plan, oversight, maintenance and reconciliation of ISO stock ledger, and preparation, planning and execution of bi-annual internal ISO markets. · Oversight of all TMA Business Development efforts including marketing; customer outreach; corporate briefs; teaming and teaming agreements; proposal support including pink/red team participation and attendance at symposiums, seminars, conferences and monthly IC-related business groups. · Oversight and management of Human Resources (HR) activities, to include yearly reviews, oversight and maintenance of TMA health care plans, day-to-day employee-related HR duties, and compliance. · Registered ITAR agent for TMA

description: Senior software developer on a number of complex X-Midas based SIGINT processing applications/ systems for programs for the Intelligence Community. Systems include Real-Time Signal Quality Assurance (RTSQA), XHCC, SUMMIT, X-FILES, HERETIC, SALEM, and ELCC2. Expertise as an X-Midas software application developer and lead technical software integrator, supporting all aspects of the software lifecycle on rapid development QRC and production projects. Duties included software design, coding, integration, testing and fielding of SIGINT systems and required extensive worldwide project TDY travel. Also collaborated with STL (now DRS) to develop X-Midas based control software for many of their specialized DSP devices. Other efforts included network administration, system administration, security and logistics support.

description: Three years of OCONUS support in the Site Systems Engineering (SSE) lab at JDFPG, Alice Springs Australia. Duties started as stay-behind engineer (hardware and software) for the Telemetry Analysis Sub-System (TASS), a large FISINT processing system, performing enhancements, upgrades, and problem troubleshooting, resolution and configuration control. Duties soon included X-Midas based QRC agile application development, integration and support to FIS and other mission areas. Supported early X-Midas baseline development by contributing primitives such as XRTSURFace, for 3D data visualization of X-Midas data files, and XRTSAMview, for visualizing contents of Texas Memory Systems (TMS) rapid access memory devices. Created the XSTL option tree (macros and primitives) that allowed visualization of and mouse control over the STL Digital Switch Matrixes. Created the TPLAID option tree that allowed automated signal platform classification of “T”-type signals. Also presented X-Midas training to local site personnel.

description: Seven years of experience as a lead software developer, supporting design, development, integration and deployment of many efforts supporting National contracts. Many tasks involved programming real-time applications using specialized hardware (i.e. array processors); primarily in FISINT and ELINT domains. Most of these efforts were focused around the National Telemetry Processing Center (NTPC, now NSPC) (Peevey, Rissman, Rootstock, Rushhour), but also included system deliveries to third party countries (HEADSAIL II) and to the CAC Lab (MTEPP / RISE). Served as the sole Temporary Duty (TDY) engineer (software, hardware, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) infrastructure) for a multi-month deployment to a third party country (HEADSAIL II). Served as technical lead and Program Manager for an upgrade to an ELINT processing system (DENTIN). Supported an R&D effort to design, develop, configure and install ruggedized SIGINT processing systems on an Army platform (SHIELDS). Supported the development of a small FISINT system for treaty verification that was delivered to Russia (START) and served as lead Project Security for many of the above capabilities.

description: Conducted signals intelligence (SIGINT) activities and operations. Performed operator and analyst duties to exploit electronic intelligence (ELINT), foreign instrumentation signals intelligence (FISINT), and PROFORMA activities. Employed signals exploitation activities to support electronic warfare (EW) operations. Operated electronic search and related equipment. Searched and exploited signal activity throughout the radio frequency spectrum. Operated electromagnetic receiving and recording systems to monitor, acquire, collect, and exploit electro-magnetic transmissions. Performed and oversaw signals collection and analysis functions. Analyzes electromagnetic transmission characteristics. Determined line of bearing or origin point, external characteristics, and parameters of electromagnetic transmissions. Operated signals analysis and data processing equipment. Extracted data from electromagnetic signals and reports results. Evaluated electromagnetic transmission exploitation to ensure characteristics are accurately determined, documented and reported. Developed and maintained automated databases and operational logs. Recorded equipment status, signals characteristics, and analytical findings. Prepared and evaluated reports. Assembled operational and technical information. Performed quality control. Inspected and evaluated SIGINT, ELINT, FISINT, PROFORMA, and EW support activities. Performed fusion analysis. Planed, organized, and directed electromagnetic signals exploitation activities. Managed allotted resources for SIGINT, ELINT, FISINT, PROFORMA, and EW operations and analysis activities. Identified responsibilities for overseeing operations, intelligence analysis, and data reduction functions. Planned operations and analysis functions and devised techniques to improve operations.

description: Cyberspace System Administrator Manager with 4 years’ experience: USAF Intelligence Surveillance Reconnaissance, Ft Gordon, GA •Directly supervised over 200+ NSA Joint Military personnel. Teamed with NSA personnel and, engaged in over two thousand Intelligence Operations and provided directions for: 50+ contract and manpower programs, and sole liaison to send/receive equipment for mission operations. •Network Security Officer for the NSA Directorate that established and maintained over 200+ accounts with the authority of to implement restrictions and user rights. •Managed 45 support personnel to ensure security regulations were followed and that installation, command and agency security standards were met. •Built 30 computer modules for Cyberspace Computer Network Exploitation (CNE) missions. •Maintained $4 million dollar systems architecture for CNE operations and 1 of 4 Project Managers overseeing $2.5 million dollar annual budget for CNE cyberspace systems infrastructure. •Coordinated 30 firewall upgrades on over 1,000 network systems was the Maintainer and scheduler for over 3,000 Computer Network Exploitation (CNE) cyberspace missions. •Tested and troubleshoots network and telecommunications equipment. •Assisted Operations Personnel in Tier 1 fault management efforts, troubleshoots, and repaired and replaced all failed network devices. Restored system outages and gave Tier 2/3 technical support for daily mission operations. •Received network, communications, and related operating systems from various commercial sources; maintained an inventory of all network hardware and software. Installed, configured, and trouble-shoots network and application server hardware, operating system software, and peripheral network equipment such as routers, bridges, cabling system, network interface cards, modems, multiplexers, and concentrators.

description: Senior SIGINT Analyst: •Utilized state of the art computers and manipulated sophisticated SIGINT software programs and analysis tools such as ANCHORY, MAUI, SURREY, AIRGAP, CIED, ARCGIS, ArcView, Google Earth, Analyst Notebook, CINEPLEX, GATEKEEPER, CPE, CHATTER, CINEPLEX, INTELINK, WISE, PATHFINDER and other tool/collection platforms to perform in-depth analysis on over 7,000 high interest entities. •Orchestrated and instructed 10 SIGINT training programs for 250 joint personnel of Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines, & NSA Civilians. Developed internet database that cataloged over 10K high priority SIGINT mission operations. Collaborated with multiple intelligence agencies and fused information to create over 100 intelligence briefs for NSA Senior Intelligence Leadership. •Senior Operations Analyst that partnered with the Office of Naval Intelligence and shaped strategies on naval tactics by satisfying over 800 ELINT operations. Drafted over 300 tech ELINT reports and these reports were used to brief the Director of Operations at the Defense Intelligence Agency. •Performed over 100 PROFORMA mission operations, trained 40 civilian personnel and increased operational production by 50%. Processed and disseminated trend analysis on over 2,000 ELINT operations. Senior HUMINT/SIGINT Analyst: •Senior SIGINT/HUMINT Analyst at the Strategic Debriefing Center (SDC) that led 10 joint personnel and provided all source intelligence and analytical support to 20 Interrogators. •HUMINT Analyst for over 700 interrogation operations in the SDC at the Detention Facility in Parwan, Afghanistan awarded the Bronze Star. •Processed over 80 intelligence information reports that shaped US National Policies. •Guided over 400 interrogations of high value detainees for Battle Space Owners. •Conducted over 1,000 hours of behavioral analysis that provided detailed analysis on interrogation operations. Performed SIGINT tasks to support over 300 Special Operations against high valued targets.

description:  Provided leadership for Counter Narcotics Network development and target development for Regional Cmd West (RCW) & Combined Joint Interagency Taskforce – NEXUS (CJIATF-N) for five months and provided invaluable support to International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) and Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA).  Answered 700 formal and informal request-for-information (RFI), 6 corrupt government officials were placed on ISAF Joint Command (IJC) list for removal & 47 nomination packages develop against narcotic traffickers.  Directed 3-member team in fast-paced corporate-level intelligence activity, supporting over 700 personnel in 9 Afghanistan-wide locations and four Province in western Afghanistan in support of DEA and SF mission set.  Briefed new RCW Fusion Center Cmdr on ITOCC Cell’s mission statement and its support to ISAF and DEA.  Provided updates on key criminal insurgent groups operating in and around Afghanistan, maintained SA by identifying actionable threats, potential targets and location of High-Value Individuals (HVI) in direct support to DEA, TF and US mentored Afghans while ensuring dissemination of products to strategic and tactical units.  Utilizing my All-Source expertise provided and in-depth analysis of information of 7 operations, targeting narcotics traffickers active in Herat, Farah and Nimroz Provinces – results led to capture of 23 narcotraffickers.  Produced numerous briefing and working papers for use in current and future planning, while creating and maintaining the counter narcotics network and targeting picture for 4 western provinces within Afghanistan.  Developed over 50 target nomination packages – directly supported operations and developed criminal patron network on HVI – Joint analysis with DEA expanded capability to disrupt and negate narcotics traffickers’ ops.

description: CMSgt Flores has held various tactical, operational, and strategic level intelligence positions throughout his distinguished Air Force career. His assignments include Intelligence Analyst, 6950th Electronic Security Group, United Kingdom; Multi-mode Operator, 32nd Intelligence Squadron, Maryland; Satellite System Supervisor, 301st Intelligence Squadron, Japan; Air FISINT Supervisor, National Air and Space Intelligence Center, Ohio; Counterspace Intelligence Staff Evaluator, 76th Space Control Squadron, Colorado; Det Superintendent, Det 2 18th Intelligence Squadron, Republic of South Korea; Operations Superintendent, 544th Intelligence Group, Colorado; Wing Plans and Programs Superintendent, 21st Space Wing, Colorado; and as the Superintendent, 25th Space Range Squadron, Colorado. Chief Flores assumed his current duty position as the Overhead Collection Management Center-Field Element Superintendent, National Reconnaissance Office in June 2011. Chief Flores has deployed five times providing time critical actionable intelligence in support of Operations SOUTHERN WATCH, ENDURING FREEDOM, and IRAQI FREEDOM. CMSgt Flores’ military education includes the Airman Leadership School, Non-commissioned Officer Academy, Senior Non-commissioned Officer Academy, Senior Enlisted Joint Professional Military Education Course, and the Senior Enlisted Intelligence Master Skills course. He has also completed the Defense Acquisition University Acquisition 101 course, National Security Space Institute Space 300 course, United Sates Navy Intermediate Signals Intelligence Analysis course (Honor Graduate), United States Army Foreign Instrumentation Signals Intelligence course (Honor Graduate) and numerous other technical and leadership courses. Chief Flores has earned an Associate of Applied Science Degree in Communications Application Technology from the Community College of the Air Force and a Bachelor of Science in Sports and Health Management from the American Military University.

description: Principal advisor to the Director of the Intelligence Analysis Directorate, a 2 star Iraqi General, on substantive, analytical, and procedural issues pertaining to integrative assessments for the Iraq Intelligence Community. ~ Responsible for research and development of equipment and techniques to solve communications and intelligence systems infrastructure gaps between, Coalition, Iraqi commands, Iraqi law enforcement agencies, and other government agencies. ~ Taught and modeled the TCPED process for Iraqi Counterparts. ~ Enabled and encouraged the continued development of the Analyst Working Group. Facilitated maximum participation by all elements of the Iraqi Ministry of Defense. ~ Global War on Terror Civilian Service Award–Senior Advisor to the Intelligence Analysis Directorate, Directorate General for Intelligence and Security, Ministry of Defense, Iraq Training and Advisory Team, Iraq from 24 November 2008 to 13 June 2009. ~ Achievement Medal for Civilian Service–Mentored the Iraqi leadership to produce strategic-focused Prioritized Intelligence Requirements that used the intelligence cycle to ensure information flow and deliver critical information to decision makers in a timely manner.

description:  Provided leadership for Counter Narcotics Network development and target development for Regional Cmd West (RCW) & Combined Joint Interagency Taskforce – NEXUS (CJIATF-N) for five months and provided invaluable support to International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) and Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA).  Answered 700 formal and informal request-for-information (RFI), 6 corrupt government officials were placed on ISAF Joint Command (IJC) list for removal & 47 nomination packages develop against narcotic traffickers.  Directed 3-member team in fast-paced corporate-level intelligence activity, supporting over 700 personnel in 9 Afghanistan-wide locations and four Province in western Afghanistan in support of DEA and SF mission set.  Briefed new RCW Fusion Center Cmdr on ITOCC Cell’s mission statement and its support to ISAF and DEA.  Provided updates on key criminal insurgent groups operating in and around Afghanistan, maintained SA by identifying actionable threats, potential targets and location of High-Value Individuals (HVI) in direct support to DEA, TF and US mentored Afghans while ensuring dissemination of products to strategic and tactical units.  Utilizing my All-Source expertise provided and in-depth analysis of information of 7 operations, targeting narcotics traffickers active in Herat, Farah and Nimroz Provinces – results led to capture of 23 narcotraffickers.  Produced numerous briefing and working papers for use in current and future planning, while creating and maintaining the counter narcotics network and targeting picture for 4 western provinces within Afghanistan.  Developed over 50 target nomination packages – directly supported operations and developed criminal patron network on HVI – Joint analysis with DEA expanded capability to disrupt and negate narcotics traffickers’ ops.

description:  Manages, coordinates, and controls delegation of responsibilities in six unique work centers. description: Retired 1 June 2014 after Serving over 35 years active and reserve time. Served in the Surface, Air, and Intel community (Cryptoligic). Spent the last 10 years with my CT buddies supporting operations within what is now known as the IDC community. I will miss all of you. Keep up the fight and do the right thing, which we know can sometimes be hard in today's military. When all is said and done it is about the person next to you and not the power plays of those we sometimes find ourselves serving. Just remember that we all swore an oath that we "will support and defend the Constitution of the United States against all enemies, foreign or domestic...". Do your duty and may God keep you safe while you keep us safe from those who would do us harm.

description: Analyze ground-based, ship borne and unidentified radar emitters for numerous agencies. Accomplishes in-depth all-source analysis to ascertain physical and electronic parameters of the radar and to verify and validate each determination. Represent the local government customer at numerous conferences, working groups, and analytical exchanges in support of the contract. Familiar with all community ELINT tools - particularly strong with MARTES, PASS, SASS, ITAS, DASS/ESP, CED, IEP and CATS toolsuites. Daily Duties - Performed all source detailed analysis of technical data in support of customer contract. Technical Lead for Northrop Grumman. Prepare technical reports; advise collection efforts and site tasking. Ensure database updates are made to include CED as well as other local and national databases. Mentor contractor and government personnel assigned to the customer's Technical ELINT Branch. Trained numerous contractor and government personnel on the use of IEP data and PASS/ITAS, DASS/ESP tool suite. Interactive Processing Specialist (IPS) - Operational support to a real-time processing and reporting system on the Paragon project. Knowledge in computer-based processing systems, analog and digital processors, data processing and communications theory. Working knowledge in FORTRAN and C programming languages as well as SUN/UNIX and CYBER/NOS operating systems. Collected, processed, analyzed and reported new and unusual ELINT emissions. PASS/SASS/ITAS Trainer - Provided demonstrations and OJT to customer personnel ensuring proper use of all analog and digital equipment. RDT/E - Assisted in the test and evaluation of new hardware and software systems for inclusion into PASS/ITAS and future collection/analysis equipment.

description: Integral member of the SMD's Army Space Control team supporting the USASMDC/ARSTRAT contract. Sparta’s task lead running the Army Task Order (XX) working with government customers, prime contractor (BAE SYSTEMS) and materiel developers to integrate capabilities into effective Space Control systems. Primary responsibility is to lead validation, verification, and testing activities prior to sell-off to the customer. Also responsible for developing support materials such as technical manuals, operational checklists, Development Test (DT) plans, Operational Test and Evaluation (OT&E) plans, training materials, and conducting training of government personnel. A secondary task on this contract is to review/update existing technical manuals, operational checklists, and training materials per government and prime contractor direction for existing Army Space Control capabilities.

description: Mental Health First Aid is an 8-hour training course designed to give members of the public key skills to help someone who is developing a mental health problem or experiencing a mental health crisis. The evidence behind the program demonstrates that it does build mental health literacy, helping the public identify, understand and respond to signs of mental illness. The Mental Health First Aid program runs 8 hours and may be offered in a variety of formats. Most often, it is conducted as one long 1-day seminar, or two 4-hour events spaced over a short period of time. A comfortable room with power point projection capabilities is required for the hosting organization. The minimum class size is 10 and the cost per person is $100.00. Cost includes individual training manual, certificate, and light snacks. For more information contact arlierogers@yahoo.com.

description: With over 10 years’ experience in contract cleaning, we’ve seen the problems many businesses face when it comes to keeping computer and IT equipment clean. Traditional cleaning companies are often reluctant to clean IT equipment and indeed rarely have the technical expertise and correct products to properly care for expensive IT kit. As a result, we were finding that the most commonly touched surfaces in offices were never being adequately cleaned. Computer equipment was becoming dirty and germ ridden – costing businesses thousands of pounds in staff sickness and IT downtime. We realised that companies needed a practical solution to this problem and so established Hygiene IT - a specialist cleaning provider offering a wide range of technical cleaning services to businesses in Harrogate, Leeds and across Yorkshire.and all parts of the U.K

description: The battalion S-6 officer and communications chief lead the Signal Regiment’s front-line Soldiers. Battalions are equipped with network and systems enablers providing capabilities that in the past were only provided at echelons brigade and higher. These enablers (for example, Blue Force Tracking [BFT], combat service support [CSS] satellite communications [SATCOM], and the command post node [CPN]) require greater external coordination than earlier systems. The battalion S-6 officer is responsible for the supervision of all automated information systems, network management, computer network defense (CND), electromagnetic spectrum operations (EMSO), and information assurance (IA). The primary signal operations planner is also an active member of the staff planning during the MDMP. He determines the supportability and feasibility of the signal plan versus the scheme of maneuver. The brigade S-6 officer, as a principal staff officer, interacts closely with the brigade commander, executive officer, operations staff officer (S-3), and other staff officers to determine specific or unique communications and network requirements. The brigade S-6 officer and his staff plan the communications and information systems support (to include EMSO) for the brigade, brigade command posts (CPs), and subordinate units organic to, assigned to, or operating within the brigade AO. The brigade S-6 section is organized to best support the commander’s intent. This section addresses the roles and responsibilities of the brigade S-6. Unless specifically noted, these roles and responsibilities apply to both the BCT S-6 officer and the modular support brigade S-6 officer.

description: Special Projects Officer (S3) of the 111th Military Intelligence Brigade, a 5,000-person training brigade consisting of four subordinate battalions located at three geographically separate locations, responsible for executing MI IET, IMT PME and Functional courses for over 10,000 students annually. Provides oversight over special projects as tasked by the BDE S3; including the development of plans and implementation of new initiatives in support of 58 courses; coordinates with USAICoE G3, TRADOC, and other external organizations as required. An BDE SPO has staffing responsibility for planning the operations, organization, and training as directed by the BDE S3 and the BDE Commander. The BDE SPO and assistants works closely with the BDE AS3, BDE S3 and DCO to accomplish the mission. The BDE S3 writes operational directives and plans and writes tactical orders, field training exercises, and training schedules. The BDE SPO, BDE AS3,and BDE S3 prepares Courses of Action (COA) and recommends actions or decisions to the Regiment/Brigade Commander for the accomplishment of the mission. As the BDE SPS3, the BDE S3 shop utmost concerned is with Planning, Training, Control, and Supervision of Operations in TRADOC and prepares detailed plans which support execution of policies and strategy. Adheres to strict policies and standards for unit readiness and supervises BN TRADOC unit efforts thru US Army standards of unit readiness to meet MOS / AIT standards. Is the TNG subject matter expert in (SME) in the “How To” of training, as well as development and management of training functions. Prepares and reviews operations and concept plans to include real world simulation exercises in TRADOC to prepare future soldiers full spectrum missions upon meeting MOS/AIT graduation standards.

Directs tasking of intelligence collection assets; produces threat estimates to support doctrine, training; and combat developments; ensures proper dissemination of intelligence information and products; manages interrogation operations of enemy prisoners of war and line crossers; interprets imagery from overhead and other systems; directs counterintelligence and operational security operations; performs clandestine human intelligence operations and manages signals intelligence operations including jamming and participating in performing deception operations. Manages these tasks at all echelons. Coordinates, supervises, and participates in all-source current intelligence indications and warnings, threat analysis, and general intelligence activities focusing on the intentions, geography, and military capabilities of foreign nations, with primary focus on the ground forces. Develops collection and production requirements, and the acquisition of information and intelligence including targeting of strategic collection resources. Evaluates, interprets, analyzes, and produces general intelligence products in support of Department of Defense requirements.

description: FIELD 0311INFANTRY: trained in infantry weapons, combat operations, and battlefield awareness; employing a variety of weapons, and through communications links, supporting arms including artillery, naval gunfire, and close air support; sea-based, capable of the full spectrum of combat, day or night, on trucks, assault vehicles, assault craft, or vertical assault aircraft; able to secure and defend self and vital terrain by repelling the enemy's assault by fire, maneuver, and close combat. The riflemen employ the M16A2 service rifle, the M203 grenade launcher and the squad automatic weapon (SAW). Riflemen are the primary scouts, assault troops, and close combat forces available to the MAGTF. They are the foundation of the Marine infantry organization, and as such are the nucleus of the fire team in the rifle squad, the scout team in the LAR squad, scout snipers in the infantry battalion, and reconnaissance or assault team in the reconnaissance units. Noncommissioned officers are assigned as fire team leaders, scout team leaders, rifle squad leaders, or rifle platoon guides. FIELD 1833, TANK AND ASSAULT AMPHIBIOUS VEHICLE: The tank and assault amphibian vehicle operation, employment, maneuver, and maintenance of tracked vehicles in the combined arms environment during both amphibious assaults and subsequent land operations ashore. Marines entering this OccFld receive MOS 1800, Basic Tank and Assault Amphibious Vehicle Crewman. After entry into OccFld 18 and assignment of a basic 1800 MOS, personnel specialize in either the M1A1 tank or the assault amphibious vehicle are assigned MOS 1812, or 1833 respectively. As members of an AAV crew or unit, AAV crewmen perform various duties incident to the operation and maintenance of assault amphibious vehicles and the up-gunned weapons station (UGWS) MK19 40 MM/50 CAL. M2. AAV crewman prepares AAVs for the tactical employment of troops and equipment during ship to shore movement and subsequent operations ashore.

description: 2012 NSA Washington Operational Performer of the Year 2012 NSOC Military Performer of the Year, Senior Enlisted 2012 S2J Weapons & Space Military Performer of the Year, Senior Enlisted 2012 NSOC Military Performer of the Quarter for the 4th Quarter, Senior Enlisted 2012 S2J Military Performer of the Quarter for 3rd Quarter, Senior Enlisted 2014 NSOC Military Performer of the Quarter for the 1st Quarter, Senior Enlisted National Security Operations Center (NSOC) focal point relating to Technical SIGINT disciplines (ELINT, FISINT, PROFORMA, OPIR); provides timely mapping, graphics, and analysis to leadership of threats & scenarios about deployed weapon systems and in development Liaison with Defense Special Missile and Aerospace Center (DEFSMAC); alerting NSOC on missile and space events; performs near-real-time analysis of events using multi-discipline methods Composes executive level briefings on global and evolving events relating to foreign weapons and space systems, deployed weapons systems, in research and development (R&D) Collaborates with developers to NSOC Common Operating Picture (COP); maintains total situational awareness of world events, operations of U.S., Allied and coalition forces; remains cognizant of global situations; provides cryptologic support to U.S. Military Commands and IC Uses multi-source SIGINT data and feeds to monitor maritime proliferation of weapons; creates graphical slides and written input to wrap-ups on significant air and air defense events; answers COCOM time-sensitive requests for information (RFI); recognizes ELINT parameters of radar and correlates to function, all supporting strategic, tactical, and operational plans and products Instrumental in U.S. Air Force F-16 aircraft Personal Recovery (PR) event. Through utilization of streaming data on Common Operating Picture (COP) and coordination. Pilot rescued

description: Leads, manages, supervises, and performs force protection duties, including use of deadly force to protect personnel and resources. Protects nuclear and conventional weapons systems and other resources. Develops plans, policies, procedures, and detailed instructions to implement SF programs. Plans, organizes, and schedules SF activities. Provides oversight, guidance, and assistance to commanders with the application of information, personnel, and industrial security programs. Operates pass and registration activities. Supervises and trains SF augmentees. Defends personnel, equipment, and resources from hostile forces. Operates in various field environments, performs individual, and team patrol movements, both mounted and dismounted, tactical drills, battle procedures, convoys, military operations other than war, antiterrorism duties, and other special duties. Operates communications equipment, vehicles, intrusion detection equipment, crew-served weapons, and other special purpose equipment. Applies self-aid buddy care, life saving procedures, including cardiopulmonary resuscitation, as first responder to accident and disaster scenes.

description: Bolaget Skid-VM i Falun 2015 AB bildades av Svenska Skidförbundet och Falu kommun i juni 2010. Uppdraget är att förbereda och genomföra skid-VM i längdskidor, backhoppning och nordisk kombinationden 18 februari-1 mars 2015. Kommunikationschefen har övergripande ansvar för Falun2015:s PR-arbete och kommunikation. Däri ingår bland annat: • Framtagande och implementering av kommunikationsplattform • Redaktionellt innehåll i egna kommunikationskanaler • Genomförande av medieaktiviteter • Planering och uppbyggnad av VM-redaktionen Dessutom inbegriper arbetet följande: • Delaktighet i framtagande av vision, mål och strategier för VM • Kontakter med externa parter så som Internationella Skidförbundet och Riksidrottsförbundet • Nära samarbete med kommunikationschefer för ägare och partners • Sekreterare i LOC Advisory Board och VM-bolagets styrelse

Kampanjkoordinator, baserad i Falun • Vara spindeln i nätet för kampanjens projekt- och styrgrupp • Rapportera till kampanjledaren Parallellt med arbetet som kampanjkoordinator arbetade jag även med information och kommunikation för SSF, vilket bl.a. innefattade: • skriva pressreleaser och redaktionella texter till SSF:s webbplats • Koordinera Snösponsringsprojektet, ett samarbete med huvudsponsorn Vattenfall där skidklubbar kunde ansöka om bidrag till specifika projekt inom klubben.

description: Hösten 2009 genomfördes World Cup i bandy för första gången i sin 75 åriga historia på annan ort än Ljusdal. SAIK fick i uppdrag att arrangera turneringen i nybyggda Göransson Arena, som invigdes på våren samma år. Detta var första gången ett stort evenemang hölls i Göransson Arena. 16 lag från olika nationer deltog i turneringen. • Strukturera, planera, genomföra och ansvara för allt arbete inför och under World Cup. Här ingick, förutom det sportsliga, även volontärer, biljetter, ackrediteringar, boende, säkerhet, PR, sponsorer, evenemang/ceremonier • Leda SAIK:s kanslipersonal i deras arbete med World Cup • Bemöta media • Samarbeta med Göransson Arena, Sandvikens kommun, samt lokala näringsidkare • Efterarbete i form av utvärdering och dokumentation • Rapportera till SAIK:s styrelse

description: IDTM is a Stockholm-based independent company that provides anti-doping management services to sports organisations around the world, including the World Anti-Doping Agency. - Assisting IDTM’s clients with keeping an effective anti-doping programme. - Co-ordinating the FIS (Int’l Ski Federation) anti-doping programme for the Nordic Ski World Cup and for the Alpine Ski World Cup together with Prof. Bengt Saltin (at that time FIS Anti-Doping Expert and Medical Committee Chairman). - Establishing and keeping up the cooperation with other clients, e.g. ICF (canoe), FIM (motorcycle), Saga d’Aventure (multisport), DMSB (German Motorcycle Federation). - Responsible for budgets, results, offers, and operational issues. - Reporting to the Managing Director of IDTM. Event Management: Managing doping control logistics at the following events: - FIS Nordic World Ski Championships, Sapporo 2007: FIS representative for doping control, which included being the link between FIS and the japanese Anti-Doping Agency. This was done on consultancy contract with IDTM. - Winter Olympic Games, Turin 2006: responsible for FIS blood testing. - FIS Nordic World Ski Championships, Oberstdorf 2005: FIS representative for doping controls, which included being the link between FIS and the german Anti-Doping Agency. - FIS Alpine World Ski Championships, Bormio 2005 – responsible for blood testing. - FIS Nordic World Ski Championships, Val di Fiemme 2003 – responsible for blood testing. - FINA Swimming World Championships, Moscow 2002 – responsible for blood and urine testing (see WADA Independent Observers Report at www.wada-ama.org).

description: Provided all-source intelligence support to a joint headquarters responsible directly to the National Command Authority for strategic operations of national significance. Served as a core member of the Joint Planning Group (JPG), performing time-sensitive and enroute mission planning that enabled U.S. Special Operations Command’s elite units to conduct highly specialized, surgical, and sensitive operations worldwide. Provided Intel targeting support for operations against Afghan and Iraqi high value targets. As the senior intelligence officer aboard the airborne Command and Control platform during the initial assault into Afghanistan, fused all-source intelligence, dynamically re-tasked ISR assets and nominated targets for fires. Deployed as the lead DoD Intelligence officer to an Interagency Task Force that included the FBI and NYPD law enforcement.

description: Provided space force enhancement support to the CENTCOM and SOCOM staffs advising them on the capabilities and limitations of all space-based assets; US, Russian and Grey Space. These included: communications, navigation, weather, warning and surveillance. Deployed to the Combined Air Operations Center (CAOC), Riyadh, Saudi Arabia in support of Operation SOUTHERN WATCH, enforcing the Iraqi southern no-fly zone. Provided DSP data to warn of impending and actual southern no-fly zone infractions. Coordinated and supervised all theater ballistic missile (TBM) exercises. Provided daily GPS accuracy predictions that supported targeting and timing of the employment of precision-guided munitions.

description: Worked with the Defense Special Missile and Aeronautics Center (DEFSMAC/NSA) and NSA CSG rep to track Indications and Warnings (I&W) of impending Red and Grey space and missile launch activity. Fused SIGINT (COMINT), ELINT (telemetry), DSP (Infrared/thermal) data, IMINT, and OSINT to provide the Command Director and the Space and Missile Warning Center crews with intelligence needed to recommend a threat assessment to the National Command Authority. Monitored and reported on the launch preparations and movement of Russian Strategic Rocket Forces and ballistic missile and attack submarines. Tracked and reported on Russian long-range aviation activity and maintained situational awareness of ongoing conflicts in the Caucuses and elsewhere around the world. Tracked and reported all pending space re-entries that might be interpreted as an attack against North America and help the Intelligence Community track Russian and Chinese space surveillance capabilities. Monitored and reported Indications and Warnings related to the global Warning Problems and changes to the WATCHCON status.

description: Bolaget Skid-VM i Falun 2015 AB bildades av Svenska Skidförbundet och Falu kommun i juni 2010. Uppdraget är att förbereda och genomföra skid-VM i längdskidor, backhoppning och nordisk kombinationden 18 februari-1 mars 2015. Kommunikationschefen har övergripande ansvar för Falun2015:s PR-arbete och kommunikation. Däri ingår bland annat: • Framtagande och implementering av kommunikationsplattform • Redaktionellt innehåll i egna kommunikationskanaler • Genomförande av medieaktiviteter • Planering och uppbyggnad av VM-redaktionen Dessutom inbegriper arbetet följande: • Delaktighet i framtagande av vision, mål och strategier för VM • Kontakter med externa parter så som Internationella Skidförbundet och Riksidrottsförbundet • Nära samarbete med kommunikationschefer för ägare och partners • Sekreterare i LOC Advisory Board och VM-bolagets styrelse

description: I ett år arbetade Svenska Skidförbundet, Falu Kommun och region Dalarna med kandidaturen om att få arrangera VM i längdskidor, backhoppning och nordisk kombination i Falun 2015. Efter ett års kampanjarbete, där man kandiderade mot tre starka konkurrenter, fick Falun uppdraget att arrangera skid-VM 2015. description: Hösten 2009 genomfördes World Cup i bandy för första gången i sin 75 åriga historia på annan ort än Ljusdal. SAIK fick i uppdrag att arrangera turneringen i nybyggda Göransson Arena, som invigdes på våren samma år. description: The FIS Alpine Ski World Championships 2007 in Åre was the biggest winter sport event ever hosted in Sweden. The event was arranged by the limited company Åre 2007 AB. - Recruitment of volunteers. - Communication with volunteers and with the different departments within the Organising Committee before and during the event. - General education of volunteers through meetings, an e-learning course, and a volunteer guide book. - Preparing for volunteers’ stay in Åre, e.g. meals, accommodation, clothes, and social activities. - The work was to a large extent handled through a database. - Writing evaluating reports after the event.

description: IDTM is a Stockholm-based independent company that provides anti-doping management services to sports organisations around the world, including the World Anti-Doping Agency. - Assisting IDTM’s clients with keeping an effective anti-doping programme. - Co-ordinating the FIS (Int’l Ski Federation) anti-doping programme for the Nordic Ski World Cup and for the Alpine Ski World Cup together with Prof. Bengt Saltin (at that time FIS Anti-Doping Expert and Medical Committee Chairman). - Establishing and keeping up the cooperation with other clients, e.g. ICF (canoe), FIM (motorcycle), Saga d’Aventure (multisport), DMSB (German Motorcycle Federation). - Responsible for budgets, results, offers, and operational issues. - Reporting to the Managing Director of IDTM. Event Management: Managing doping control logistics at the following events: - FIS Nordic World Ski Championships, Sapporo 2007: FIS representative for doping control, which included being the link between FIS and the japanese Anti-Doping Agency. This was done on consultancy contract with IDTM. - Winter Olympic Games, Turin 2006: responsible for FIS blood testing. - FIS Nordic World Ski Championships, Oberstdorf 2005: FIS representative for doping controls, which included being the link between FIS and the german Anti-Doping Agency. - FIS Alpine World Ski Championships, Bormio 2005 – responsible for blood testing. - FIS Nordic World Ski Championships, Val di Fiemme 2003 – responsible for blood testing. - FINA Swimming World Championships, Moscow 2002 – responsible for blood and urine testing (see WADA Independent Observers Report at www.wada-ama.org).

description: As General Manager of a new start up manufacturing operation I was responsible for the all aspects of the day to day running of the business, in addition to creating and implementing the structures and processes that enabled the business establish itself as the go to company for bespoke metalwork. I managed three teams, production, sales and administration ensuring the smooth interaction between each aspect of the business. As with any new start up business the role required me to take a very hands on approach to management, getting my hands dirty on the factory floor, directing sales activity, negotiating with clients, suppliers and investors all of which helped me to win the respect of my workforce and board of directors alike. The infrastructure that I have created and put into place is currently undergoing ISO:9001 accreditation, which will enable the business to grow significantly within the Business to Business market place. More importantly as a pilot business for the wider Partumis Ltd business, Partumis Metal is on track to receive the £15 million private equity investment which will enable the full launch of the Partumis web application in late 2013.

description: Working directly with entrepreneur Jim Harlow to create the concept for Partumis Ltd, the revolutionary web based application business which is set to launch in late 2013. In addition to helping to develop the business model I undertook the market and customer demand analysis which forms the basis of the business plan for what private equity investors are calling “the most ingenious business model of the 21st century” however due to confidentiality agreements I am unable to disclose too much information. The role also required me to generate and negotiate collaborative partnerships with multiple types of supplier and end users. Develop and grow the Partumis brand and organize a national university tour to promote the business. In early 2012 private equity investors in Partumis requested a pilot business be launched to test the viability of the mechanics of Partumis. My In-depth knowledge of the Partumis system and successful management of a team of designers and administrators led to my promotion to General Manager of the Partumis Metal manufacturing facility.

description: In 2009 I assumed the role of Business Development Executive for visionary logistics service provider Qlog Ltd. Already in the top 25 fastest growing businesses in the UK, it was my job to identify and liaise with potential customers, as well as growing the industrial recognition of the Qlog brand and driving the businesses marketing strategy forward. One of my primary functions was the in depth analysis of potential customers business operations to ascertain their suitability prior to our large scale investments into the business. This work included the full breakdown and analysis of all sales, production and logistics transactions over a minimum period of three years, benchmarking of incumbent service providers, reviewing all quality issues and their effect on supply chain costs, and estimating the potential cost saving that could be achieved by the customer switching over to the Qlog model. When taking on a new client Qlog invests significant funds into their business footing all of the costs of switching from their incumbent service provider and installing dedicated operators within their site. The actual costs to the client which are best explained as “no win, no fee” with achieved cost savings against their historical supply chain spend being split 50/50 between Qlog and the customer. This means that they deal with a relatively small number of highly profitable clients at any one time, and the prequalifying analysis process I performed was critical for the long term success of the business.

description: I launched my own business Danway Business Solutions Ltd in 2008 utilizing the experience that gained offering business support services to SME (Small to Medium Enterprises) while working for MAS-WM. I formed a network of locally based business service providers whose services were beneficial to small businesses including: maintenance service contracts, debt recovery, property management, communication systems, website design & hosting, HR systems and pension schemes. Working on a commission basis Danway generated its profits by recommending the companies within the network to our customers. We maximized the sales potential by requiring inter-network cross selling and purchasing as a prerequisite of membership. The business worked extremely well with customers responding to the promotional message “focus on doing what you do best and leave the rest to the experts” I resigned my Directorship in 2009 when the opportunity to work with Jim Harlow, one of the UK’s top entrepreneurs arose to prevent any conflicts of interest. Danway Business Solutions continued to trade for 12 months under the leadership of the remaining Directors until it finally became victim of the recession.

description: In 2007 on the strength of my combined manufacturing and analytical skills I went to work for the Manufacturing Advisory Service as a Research and Information Officer in a data analysis and report writing capacity replacing the then defunct Manufacturing Foundation. The primary goal of the position was to help drive forward the governments’ support of SME manufacturers by ensuring that the right levels of funding and most appropriate support facilities were in place to maximise help available within the established funding framework. The role required analysis of published data from a wide variety of industrial and government bodies as well as interacting with businesses and individuals to capture live data which was then used to write a number of different types of reports and presentation for distribution to key stake holders, internal operatives and the wider UK manufacturing base.

description: Head Hunted to form part of the new Manufacturing Improvement Team. I specialized in utilizing lean manufacturing techniques to improve the productivity of the entire manufacturing facility. Projects undertaken included: Route cause analysis of quality issues within casting processes, undertaken by monitoring temperature and energy draw fluctuations from casting furnaces via temperature and electrical probes linked up to a computer monitoring system. This data was then cross referenced against the assay results from the cast products and allowed us to identify a pattern of electrical spikes which were causing inconsistent melting temperature and thus preventing a homogeneous mix of the raw materials in the crucible. The results of the investigation allowed us to service the machine correctly with the least amount of disruption to production. The creation of Standard and machine operating procedures for over 15,000 processes across a multi-site manufacturing operation based on internally captured data. Through filming and interviewing the machine operators I produced step by step visual guides explaining how to operate and maintain each machine. This was then combined with similar step by step guides for manufacturing each of the 15,000 product variations produced by the company. This process enabled the business to retain all of the core information from an aging workforce within the business, and made training new staff significantly easier. Establishing Kanban systems for numerous production operations based on the analysis of single piece production time, supply chain through put and customer requirements. By calculating the time taken to produce one item, the time taken to order and receive the raw material feed stock and the average customer order size and lead time I was able to establish automated material reorder points so as to support the operation with the minimum levels of raw material while ensuring that process never ran out stock.

description: As the manager of the Precious Metals Purchasing department, I lead a team of 7 operators in Birmingham and at 2 satellite offices in the UK and Ireland. I was directly responsible for the creation of and successful adherence to business and marketing strategies as well as the formulation and delivery of training programs. Evaluation of the existing departmental structure and operating procedures highlighted several bottle necks which I removed to streamline the entire process allowing us to almost double our through put. During my first year in charge I increased the profitability by 20% taking the department through the £1 million pound turnover mark for the first time in the department’s long history. On the basis of my successful management and transformation of the department I was recruited to join the company’s new Manufacturing Improvement Team. I take a lot of pride in knowing that I was replaced with a dedicated Director to continue the fantastic work that I had begun, and retained an advisory role over the department to deal with technical and training issues.

description: Provided all-source intelligence support to a joint headquarters responsible directly to the National Command Authority for strategic operations of national significance. Served as a core member of the Joint Planning Group (JPG), performing time-sensitive and enroute mission planning that enabled U.S. Special Operations Command’s elite units to conduct highly specialized, surgical, and sensitive operations worldwide. Provided Intel targeting support for operations against Afghan and Iraqi high value targets. As the senior intelligence officer aboard the airborne Command and Control platform during the initial assault into Afghanistan, fused all-source intelligence, dynamically re-tasked ISR assets and nominated targets for fires. Deployed as the lead DoD Intelligence officer to an Interagency Task Force that included the FBI and NYPD law enforcement.

description: Provided space force enhancement support to the CENTCOM and SOCOM staffs advising them on the capabilities and limitations of all space-based assets; US, Russian and Grey Space. These included: communications, navigation, weather, warning and surveillance. Deployed to the Combined Air Operations Center (CAOC), Riyadh, Saudi Arabia in support of Operation SOUTHERN WATCH, enforcing the Iraqi southern no-fly zone. Provided DSP data to warn of impending and actual southern no-fly zone infractions. Coordinated and supervised all theater ballistic missile (TBM) exercises. Provided daily GPS accuracy predictions that supported targeting and timing of the employment of precision-guided munitions.

description: Worked with the Defense Special Missile and Aeronautics Center (DEFSMAC/NSA) and NSA CSG rep to track Indications and Warnings (I&W) of impending Red and Grey space and missile launch activity. Fused SIGINT (COMINT), ELINT (telemetry), DSP (Infrared/thermal) data, IMINT, and OSINT to provide the Command Director and the Space and Missile Warning Center crews with intelligence needed to recommend a threat assessment to the National Command Authority. Monitored and reported on the launch preparations and movement of Russian Strategic Rocket Forces and ballistic missile and attack submarines. Tracked and reported on Russian long-range aviation activity and maintained situational awareness of ongoing conflicts in the Caucuses and elsewhere around the world. Tracked and reported all pending space re-entries that might be interpreted as an attack against North America and help the Intelligence Community track Russian and Chinese space surveillance capabilities. Monitored and reported Indications and Warnings related to the global Warning Problems and changes to the WATCHCON status.

description: As General Manager of a new start up manufacturing operation I was responsible for the all aspects of the day to day running of the business, in addition to creating and implementing the structures and processes that enabled the business establish itself as the go to company for bespoke metalwork. I managed three teams, production, sales and administration ensuring the smooth interaction between each aspect of the business. As with any new start up business the role required me to take a very hands on approach to management, getting my hands dirty on the factory floor, directing sales activity, negotiating with clients, suppliers and investors all of which helped me to win the respect of my workforce and board of directors alike. The infrastructure that I have created and put into place is currently undergoing ISO:9001 accreditation, which will enable the business to grow significantly within the Business to Business market place. More importantly as a pilot business for the wider Partumis Ltd business, Partumis Metal is on track to receive the £15 million private equity investment which will enable the full launch of the Partumis web application in late 2013.

description: Working directly with entrepreneur Jim Harlow to create the concept for Partumis Ltd, the revolutionary web based application business which is set to launch in late 2013. In addition to helping to develop the business model I undertook the market and customer demand analysis which forms the basis of the business plan for what private equity investors are calling “the most ingenious business model of the 21st century” however due to confidentiality agreements I am unable to disclose too much information. The role also required me to generate and negotiate collaborative partnerships with multiple types of supplier and end users. Develop and grow the Partumis brand and organize a national university tour to promote the business. In early 2012 private equity investors in Partumis requested a pilot business be launched to test the viability of the mechanics of Partumis. My In-depth knowledge of the Partumis system and successful management of a team of designers and administrators led to my promotion to General Manager of the Partumis Metal manufacturing facility.

description: In 2009 I assumed the role of Business Development Executive for visionary logistics service provider Qlog Ltd. Already in the top 25 fastest growing businesses in the UK, it was my job to identify and liaise with potential customers, as well as growing the industrial recognition of the Qlog brand and driving the businesses marketing strategy forward. One of my primary functions was the in depth analysis of potential customers business operations to ascertain their suitability prior to our large scale investments into the business. This work included the full breakdown and analysis of all sales, production and logistics transactions over a minimum period of three years, benchmarking of incumbent service providers, reviewing all quality issues and their effect on supply chain costs, and estimating the potential cost saving that could be achieved by the customer switching over to the Qlog model. When taking on a new client Qlog invests significant funds into their business footing all of the costs of switching from their incumbent service provider and installing dedicated operators within their site. The actual costs to the client which are best explained as “no win, no fee” with achieved cost savings against their historical supply chain spend being split 50/50 between Qlog and the customer. This means that they deal with a relatively small number of highly profitable clients at any one time, and the prequalifying analysis process I performed was critical for the long term success of the business.

description: I launched my own business Danway Business Solutions Ltd in 2008 utilizing the experience that gained offering business support services to SME (Small to Medium Enterprises) while working for MAS-WM. I formed a network of locally based business service providers whose services were beneficial to small businesses including: maintenance service contracts, debt recovery, property management, communication systems, website design & hosting, HR systems and pension schemes. Working on a commission basis Danway generated its profits by recommending the companies within the network to our customers. We maximized the sales potential by requiring inter-network cross selling and purchasing as a prerequisite of membership. The business worked extremely well with customers responding to the promotional message “focus on doing what you do best and leave the rest to the experts” I resigned my Directorship in 2009 when the opportunity to work with Jim Harlow, one of the UK’s top entrepreneurs arose to prevent any conflicts of interest. Danway Business Solutions continued to trade for 12 months under the leadership of the remaining Directors until it finally became victim of the recession.

description: In 2007 on the strength of my combined manufacturing and analytical skills I went to work for the Manufacturing Advisory Service as a Research and Information Officer in a data analysis and report writing capacity replacing the then defunct Manufacturing Foundation. The primary goal of the position was to help drive forward the governments’ support of SME manufacturers by ensuring that the right levels of funding and most appropriate support facilities were in place to maximise help available within the established funding framework. The role required analysis of published data from a wide variety of industrial and government bodies as well as interacting with businesses and individuals to capture live data which was then used to write a number of different types of reports and presentation for distribution to key stake holders, internal operatives and the wider UK manufacturing base.

description: Head Hunted to form part of the new Manufacturing Improvement Team. I specialized in utilizing lean manufacturing techniques to improve the productivity of the entire manufacturing facility. Projects undertaken included: Route cause analysis of quality issues within casting processes, undertaken by monitoring temperature and energy draw fluctuations from casting furnaces via temperature and electrical probes linked up to a computer monitoring system. This data was then cross referenced against the assay results from the cast products and allowed us to identify a pattern of electrical spikes which were causing inconsistent melting temperature and thus preventing a homogeneous mix of the raw materials in the crucible. The results of the investigation allowed us to service the machine correctly with the least amount of disruption to production. The creation of Standard and machine operating procedures for over 15,000 processes across a multi-site manufacturing operation based on internally captured data. Through filming and interviewing the machine operators I produced step by step visual guides explaining how to operate and maintain each machine. This was then combined with similar step by step guides for manufacturing each of the 15,000 product variations produced by the company. This process enabled the business to retain all of the core information from an aging workforce within the business, and made training new staff significantly easier. Establishing Kanban systems for numerous production operations based on the analysis of single piece production time, supply chain through put and customer requirements. By calculating the time taken to produce one item, the time taken to order and receive the raw material feed stock and the average customer order size and lead time I was able to establish automated material reorder points so as to support the operation with the minimum levels of raw material while ensuring that process never ran out stock.

description: As the manager of the Precious Metals Purchasing department, I lead a team of 7 operators in Birmingham and at 2 satellite offices in the UK and Ireland. I was directly responsible for the creation of and successful adherence to business and marketing strategies as well as the formulation and delivery of training programs. Evaluation of the existing departmental structure and operating procedures highlighted several bottle necks which I removed to streamline the entire process allowing us to almost double our through put. During my first year in charge I increased the profitability by 20% taking the department through the £1 million pound turnover mark for the first time in the department’s long history. On the basis of my successful management and transformation of the department I was recruited to join the company’s new Manufacturing Improvement Team. I take a lot of pride in knowing that I was replaced with a dedicated Director to continue the fantastic work that I had begun, and retained an advisory role over the department to deal with technical and training issues.
